Philip Yego and DPPS @PeopleDailyKe Several Jubilee Party MPs yesterday said they would support a referendum to amend the Constitution  as long as it aims at improving the lives of Kenyans. The legislators, who were addressing a function attended by Deputy President William Ruto, said the Constitution should only be amended to benefit a majority of Kenyans, not a few individuals. Speaking at Kaproret in Bureti, Kericho county yesterday during a church service and thanksgiving event for Kericho Women Rep Florence Bore, the leaders said they were focused on activities aimed at transforming the lives of Kenyans. Not scared The MPs included Kimani Ichungwa (Kikuyu), Kimani Ngunjiri (Bahati), Didmus Barasa (Kimilili), Purity Ngirici (Kirinyaga), Catherine Waruguru (Laikipia), Halima Mucheke (Nominated), Faith Gitau (Nyandarua), Tecla Tum (Nandi), Joyce Kameme (Machakos), Hillary Kosgei (Kipkellion West), Joseph Limo (Kipkelion East), Japeth Mutai (Bureti), Kipsengeret Koros (Soin/Sigowet) and Nelson Koech (Belgut). Kericho Governor Paul Chepkwony was also present. “We want to make it clear that we are not scared of a referendum to amend the Constitution so long as we are told how it will help Kenyans,” said Ichungwa. Ruto urged leaders to avoid politics and focus on activities that can transform the lives of Kenyans. He said Jubilee was formed to unite the country and transform the lives of Kenyans.